'''Gerry Shishin Wick''' is a [[Soto Zen]] [[Rōshi|roshi]], author, [[oceanographer]] and abbot of Great Mountain Zen Center in [[Berthoud, Colorado]], which he founded in 1996. He is one of the twelve Dharma Successors of the late [[Taizan Maezumi]], receiving [[Dharma transmission]] and a [[Zen ranks and hierarchy|Denkai]] (precept transmission) from him in 1990. Prior to it, for 24 years he underwent Zen training with [[Taizan Maezumi|Maezumi]], [[Shunryu Suzuki Roshi]] and Sochu Suzuki Roshi. He remained the president of [[White Plum Asanga]], a Zen school in the Hakuyu Taizan Maezumi lineage, from 2007 to 2014.<ref name="great">{{cite web | title = Teachers |work= Great Mountain Zen Center | url = http://gmzc.org/teachers/ | accessdate = 2014-10-17  }}</ref>

He has a [[Ph.D.]] in [[physics]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]], and has held a variety of jobs in the scientific community as well as an [[Adjunct professor|adjunct]] teaching position at [[Naropa University]] in [[Boulder, Colorado]].  He also administered the [[Zen Center of Los Angeles]] and the Kuroda Institute for the Study of Buddhism and Human Values from 1978 to 1986. In 2006, Wick received [[Dharma transmission|inka]] from [[Bernard Glassman]]. He was acknowledged as a [[Rōshi|roshi]] in 2000 at [[White Plum Asanga]], where he remained the president from 2007 to 2014, when he retired as an elder.<ref name="great"/><ref name="prebish">Prebish, 98</ref><ref name="morreale">Morreale, 134</ref>[http://www.peacemakercommunity.org/zps/family.htm]

