'''Jonathan Rée''' (born 1948) is a British freelance [[historian]] and [[philosopher]] from [[Bradford]]. Educated at Sussex University and then at Oxford, Rée was previously a Professor of Philosophy at [[Middlesex University]], but gave up a teaching career in order to "have more time to think".
He has written for the New Humanist, ''[[Evening Standard]]'', ''[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]'', ''[[Lingua Franca (magazine)|Lingua Franca]]'', ''[[London Review of Books]]'', ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]'', ''[[The Independent]]'', the ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'',<ref name="TLS: All Three Human">,{{cite news|url= http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/the_tls/tls_selections/philosophy/article2305497.ece#|title= TLS: All Three Human | work=The Times | location=London | first=Jonathan | last=Ree | date=2005-09-16 | accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref> and ''[[Rising East]]''.<ref name="Rising East: Intelligence Problems">,{{cite web|url= http://www.uel.ac.uk/risingeast/archive04/debate/clarke_ramadan_blunkett_ree_cheesman.htm#Ree|title= Rising East: Intelligence Problems|access-date= 2009-10-26|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080507134512/http://www.uel.ac.uk/risingeast/archive04/debate/clarke_ramadan_blunkett_ree_cheesman.htm#Ree|archive-date= 2008-05-07|dead-url= yes|df= }}</ref> He is frequently a guest in radio programmes such as ''[[Journeys In Thought]]'' and ''[[In Our Time (BBC Radio 4)|In Our Time]]''. In the early 1990s he presented a seven-part Channel 4 TV series (produced and broadcast in the UK) ''Talking Liberties'', which featured Rée in conversation with a number of thinkers, including [[Jacques Derrida]], [[Paul Ricoeur]], and [[Edward Said]].<ref>[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/series/21033 Talking Liberties entry in BFI database]</ref> Rée was a founding member of the British journal and group [[Radical Philosophy]].<ref name="Radical Philosophy Founding Statement">,{{cite web|url=http://www.radicalphilosophy.com/editorial/founding-statement-frontispiece|title=Radical Philosophy Founding Statement}}</ref>
