'''Men's romantic fiction''' refers to any fictional portrayal of [[romantic love]] either in film, text, or other media and is usually either told from the male protagonist's [[point of view (literature)|point of view]] or taking particular interest in the romance as viewed from a male perspective.

Although generally concerning heterosexual relationships, men's romantic fiction also includes [[gay pulp fiction|gay romantic fiction]], romance dealing with love between men.{{citation needed|date=September 2009}}

The genre of 'lad lit' also has somewhat similar connotations.

==Examples==
For example, the novels ''[[Belinda (Anne Rice novel)|Belinda]]'' by [[Anne Rice]] and ''Northern Lights'' by [[Nora Roberts]] are both told from the male protagonist's point of view. The novel ''[[Bid Time Return|Somewhere In Time]]'' (Former title: ''Bid Time Return'') by Richard Matheson is a romance told from the male protagonist point of view. It is sometimes classified as science fiction as well as romance. Other novelists such as [[Nicholas Sparks (author)|Nicholas Sparks]] who wrote ''[[A Walk to Remember]]'' and  ''[[The Notebook (novel)|The Notebook]]'' usually write from the male perspective, foregrounded by typical prefaces and diary entries at the beginning of the story.

Romantic stories told from the point of view of a male protagonist are very common among Japanese [[shounen]] and [[seinen]] [[manga]] and [[bishoujo games]]. Many of the latter contain erotic aspects in addition to the portrayal of romantic love.<ref>[http://www.erogereview.com/ Eroge Review (Not safe for work)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225080147/http://www.erogereview.com/ |date=2009-02-25 }}</ref>

