{{short description|poem by E. E. Cummings}} {{lowercase title}} {{Infobox poem |name = pity this busy monster, manunkind |author = [[E. E. Cummings]] |first = 1944 |country = US |subject = <!-- Subject(/s) --> |form = Sonnet<ref name="Jason">{{cite book|editor1-last=Jason|editor1-first=Philip K.|editor2-last=Irons-Georges|editor2-first=Tracy|title=Masterplots II: Poetry|date=2002|publisher=Salem Press|isbn=9781587650437|pages=3011-3013|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uqQjAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=3 January 2017}}</ref> |meter = Free verse |publisher = [[Henry Holt (publisher)|Henry Holt]] (1944) |lines = 14 }} "'''pity this busy monster, manunkind'''" is a poem by American poet [[E. E. Cummings]], first published in his 1944 book ''[[1 × 1]]''. It is among his best-known poems.<ref name="Bloom">{{cite book|last1=Bloom|first1=Harold|authorlink=Harold Bloom|title=E. E. Cummings|chapter=James P. Dougherty on the Third Poetic World|date=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=9781438115665|page=96|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dv1CjIIRWd0C|accessdate=13 January 2017}}</ref>
The poem laments the triumph of [[scientific progress|progress]]—defined in terms of science and technology—over nature, describing progress as a "comfortable disease", and declaring "A world of made / is not a world of born". To Cummings, the "busy monster" is a society bent on subverting nature and individual humanity—these, not "manunkind", are to be pitied. The speaker of the poem suggests in closing, and with an ironic optimism, an escape to "a hell of a good universe next door".<ref name="enotes">{{cite web|title=pity this busy monster,manunkind Summary|url=https://www.enotes.com/topics/pity-this-busy-monster-manunkind|website=eNotes|accessdate=13 January 2017}}</ref>
The poem relies on coined compound words and other wordplay to carry its meaning.<ref name="enotes"/><ref name="Widdowson">{{cite book|last1=Widdowson|first1=Henry|authorlink1=Henry Widdowson|title=Defining Issues in English Language Teaching|date=2003|publisher=Oxform University Press|isbn=9780194374453|page=48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SbtqkmYNA7MC|accessdate=13 January 2017|chapter=English as an international language}}</ref> As with many of Cummings' poems, his idiosyncratic [[orthography]] and [[grammar]] provide an immediacy to the printed words.<ref name="Bloom"/> Like other [[modernist poetry|modernist]] poets, Cummings uses unusual [[typography]] to draw focus to the [[typewriter]] as an instrument of the machine age.<ref name="enotes"/>
Cummings considered the fourteen-line poem a [[sonnet]], by his own loose definition of the term.<ref name="Jason"/><ref name="enotes"/>
