'''Prasanta Kumar Pattanaik'''<ref name=VIAF>{{cite web|title=Pattanaik, Prasanta K. (Prasanta Kumar) | url= http://viaf.org/viaf/41937213/#Pattanaik,_Prasanta_K. | publisher= Virtual International Authority File | accessdate= 29 September 2014}}</ref> (born 4 May 1943),<ref name=Congress>{{cite web |title= Pattanaik, Prasanta K. |url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n83071471.html |publisher= Library of Congress |accessdate= 29 September 2014 |quote= data sheet (b. 5-4-1943) }}</ref> is emeritus professor at the Department of Economics at the [[University of California]], a research associate for the [[Oxford Poverty & Human Development Initiative|Oxford Poverty & Human Development Initiative (OPHI)]],<ref name=OPHI>{{cite web|title=Prasanta Pattanaik|url=http://www.ophi.org.uk/about/people/prasanta-pattanaik/|publisher=[[Oxford Poverty and Human Development Initiative|Oxford Poverty & Human Development Initiative, University of Oxford]]|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> and a fellow of the [[Human Development and Capability Association]].<ref name=HDCA>{{cite web |title= HDCA fellows |url= https://hd-ca.org/about/hdca-fellows |publisher= [[Human Development and Capability Association]] | accessdate= 29 September 2014}}</ref>

Along with [[Amartya Sen]] and [[Kenneth Arrow]], Pattanaik is an advisory editor for the journal ''[[Social Choice and Welfare]]''.<ref name=Journal>{{cite web|title=Social Choice and Welfare &#124; Editorial board &#124; Advisory Editors | url= https://www.springer.com/economics/economic+theory/journal/355?detailsPage=editorialBoard | publisher= Springer |accessdate= 29 September 2014}}</ref>

== Education ==
Pattanaik gained his degree in economics from [[Utkal University]], [[Odisha|Odisha, India]]. He then went on to study for his masters and doctorate, both in economics, at the prestigious Delhi School of Economics [[University of Delhi]].<ref name=OPHI />

Pattanaik studied under, the [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Prize]] winning economist, [[Amartya Sen]] and his "leadership role" in the study of [[social choice theory]] has been acknowledged by Sen.<ref>{{citation | last = Sen | first = Amartya | author-link = Amartya Sen | contribution = Acknowledgements | editor-last = Sen | editor-first = Amartya | editor-link = Amartya Sen | title = [[The Idea of Justice|The idea of justice]] | pages = xii–xxiii | publisher = Penguin | location = London | year = 2010 | isbn = 9780141037851 | ref = harv | postscript = .}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=OM4RBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA182&lpg=PA182&dq=Prasanta+Pattanaik+The+Idea+of+Justice+Sen&source=bl&ots=0rpOeGxRdz&sig=WOkfguv1Z2mZH73oJ7j12hb2J7Q&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WvwkVJ6uDoGV7Ab60oCgBA&ved=0CCMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Prasanta%20Pattanaik&f=false Book preview.]</ref>

== Selected bibliography ==

=== Book series ===
Pattanaik is one of the series editors for the [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] series ''Studies in Choice and Welfare'',<ref name=Series>{{cite web|title=Studies in Choice and Welfare|url=https://www.springer.com/series/6869?detailsPage=titles|publisher=Springer|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> which included being co-editor of ''Rational choice and social welfare theory and applications: essays in honor of [[Kotaro Suzumura]]''.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Pattanaik  | first1 = Prasanta K. | last2 = Tadenuma | first2 = Koichi | last3 = Xu | first3 = Yongsheng | last4 = Yoshihara | first4 = Naoki | title = Rational choice and social welfare theory and applications: essays in honor of Kotaro Suzumura | publisher = Springer | series = Studies in Choice and Welfare | location = Berlin | year = 2008 | isbn = 9783540798316 }}</ref>

